VALUES
(44, 17, 19, 62, 2, 7, 8, 'new doctrine, whereof thou speakest', 'New Doctrine and Commandment Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of newness in both passages. Acts 17:19 speaks of a ''new doctrine,'' while 1 John 2:8 mentions a ''new commandment,'' suggesting a transformative message that is both old and new.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 20, 28, 8, 12, 12, 'strange things', 'Strange Things in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of ''strange things'' as both passages refer to concepts that are perceived as unfamiliar or unusual. In Acts, the ''strange things'' bring curiosity, while in Hosea, the law is regarded as a ''strange thing'' by the people.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 20, 46, 1, 23, 23, 'strange things', 'Understanding Strange Teachings', 'This connection highlights the response to unfamiliar concepts. In Acts, the audience seeks understanding of ''strange things,'' while in 1 Corinthians, the message of Christ is perceived as ''foolishness'' to the Greeks, indicating a similar struggle with new ideas.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 20, 46, 2, 14, 14, 'strange things', 'Understanding Spiritual Discernment', 'This connection highlights the challenge of understanding spiritual truths. In Acts, the inquiry about ''strange things'' reflects a desire for comprehension, while 1 Corinthians emphasizes that such understanding is beyond the natural man and requires spiritual discernment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 20, 60, 4, 4, 4, 'strange things', 'Strangeness of Beliefs', 'This connection highlights the theme of strangeness in beliefs. In Acts, the audience finds the teachings strange, while in 1 Peter, the surrounding society finds it strange that believers do not partake in their excesses.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 20, 40, 19, 23, 25, 'we would know therefore what these things mean', 'Wealth and Understanding Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding the challenges of salvation, particularly for those with wealth. Both passages emphasize the difficulty of entering the kingdom of God, prompting a desire for clarity about salvation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 20, 41, 9, 10, 10, 'what these things mean', 'Curiosity about Meaning', 'Both passages emphasize a desire to understand unfamiliar concepts. In Acts, the listeners seek to know the meaning of strange things, while in Mark, the disciples question the meaning of the rising from the dead.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 20, 41, 10, 24, 26, 'strange things to our ears', 'Astonishment at Teachings', 'Both passages emphasize astonishment in response to challenging teachings. In Acts, the listeners express curiosity about strange things, while in Mark, the disciples are astonished at Jesus'' words about wealth and salvation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 21, 55, 2, 16, 17, 'nothing else, but either to tell, or to hear some new thing', 'Connection of Vain Babblings', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of engaging in empty discussions. Acts 17:21 highlights a culture focused on ''new thing,'' while 2 Timothy 2:16 warns against ''profane and vain babblings,'' suggesting a shared concern about unproductive dialogue.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 21, 49, 5, 16, 16, 'spent their time in nothing else', 'Time and Its Value', 'This connection highlights the importance of time management in both passages. Acts 17:21 describes people spending their time on trivial pursuits, while Ephesians 5:16 emphasizes redeeming time due to the evil nature of the days.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 21, 51, 4, 5, 5, 'spent their time in nothing else', 'Wisdom and Time Management', 'This connection highlights the importance of how individuals spend their time. Both passages emphasize the need for wisdom in engaging with others, particularly in the context of redeeming time wisely.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 21, 53, 3, 11, 12, 'nothing else, but either to tell, or to hear some new thing', 'Disorderly Conduct and Busybodies', 'This connection highlights the theme of idleness and distraction in both passages. Acts 17:21 describes people who are preoccupied with ''new things,'' while 2 Thessalonians 3:11-12 addresses those who are ''busy bodies'' instead of working quietly.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 21, 54, 5, 13, 13, NULL, 'Idleness and Curiosity', 'This connection highlights the theme of idleness and the tendency to engage in trivial pursuits. Both passages emphasize a focus on distractions, whether through seeking new ideas or gossiping.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 22, 44, 25, 19, 19, 'too superstitious', 'Connection of Superstition in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''superstition'' as it relates to the beliefs of the Athenians and the accusations against Paul. This connection highlights how superstition is a recurring theme in the context of early Christian teachings.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 22, 44, 17, 16, 16, 'too superstitious', 'Idolatry and Superstition in Athens', 'Both passages emphasize the prevalence of idolatry in Athens. Paul''s observation of the city being ''wholly given to idolatry'' connects to his remark about the people being ''too superstitious,'' highlighting their misguided worship practices.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 22, 44, 19, 35, 35, 'too superstitious', 'Worship and Superstition Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of worship, with Paul addressing the superstitious nature of the Athenians and the town clerk referencing the worship of Diana in Ephesus. This connection highlights the cultural context of idolatry in both cities.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 22, 24, 10, 2, 3, 'too superstitious', 'Superstition and Heathen Practices', 'This connection highlights the theme of superstition and vain customs. Both passages address the folly of worshiping created things, with Paul noting the Athenians'' superstitions and Jeremiah warning against the customs of the heathen.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 22, 24, 50, 38, 38, 'too superstitious', 'Idolatry and Superstition Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of idolatry, as both passages address the folly of worshiping false images and idols. Paul refers to the Athenians as ''too superstitious,'' paralleling Jeremiah''s description of a land consumed by ''graven images'' and idol worship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 43, 4, 22, 22, NULL, 'Worship of the Unknown God', 'This connection highlights the theme of worshiping without full understanding. Both passages emphasize the idea of worshiping what is not fully known, with Acts referencing the ''UNKNOWN GOD'' and John stating, ''Ye worship ye know not what.''', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 48, 4, 8, 9, NULL, 'Worship of Unknown God', 'This connection highlights the theme of ignorance in worship. Both passages address the idea of serving false gods and the transition to knowing the true God.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 43, 17, 3, 3, 'TO THE UNKNOWN GOD', 'Knowledge of the True God', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowing God. In Acts, Paul refers to the ''unknown God'' that the Athenians worship, while in John, eternal life is defined as knowing the ''only true God.'' Both passages emphasize the importance of recognizing and understanding God''s true nature.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 44, 17, 30, 30, 'ignorantly worship', 'Ignorance and Divine Command', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ignorance in worship. The first passage identifies the worship of the ''UNKNOWN GOD,'' while the second addresses God''s response to such ignorance, commanding repentance.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 46, 1, 21, 21, 'UNKNOWN GOD', 'Wisdom and Ignorance in Worship', 'This connection highlights the theme of ignorance in worship and the role of divine wisdom. In Acts, the ''UNKNOWN GOD'' represents the world''s failure to recognize God, while in 1 Corinthians, it states that ''the world by wisdom knew not God.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 53, 2, 4, 4, 'whom therefore ye ignorantly worship', 'Worship of the Unknown God', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship, as both passages address the concept of what is worshipped and the nature of divinity. Acts 17:23 mentions the worship of an ''Unknown God,'' while 2 Thessalonians 2:4 discusses one who exalts himself as God, indicating a contrast in understanding divine authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 45, 1, 28, 28, NULL, 'Knowledge of God and Worship', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowledge of God and the consequences of ignoring it. In Acts, the worship of the ''UNKNOWN GOD'' reflects a lack of true understanding, while Romans discusses the rejection of God in knowledge leading to a reprobate mind.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 24, 11, 8, 27, 27, 'dwelleth not in temples made with hands', 'God''s Presence Beyond Temples', 'Both passages emphasize that God cannot be contained within physical structures. Acts 17:24 states that God ''dwelleth not in temples made with hands,'' while 1 Kings 8:27 questions if God can dwell on earth, noting that even the heavens cannot contain Him.', 'theme', 0.685, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 24, 5, 10, 14, 14, 'Lord of heaven and earth', 'God''s Sovereignty Over Creation', 'Both passages emphasize God''s ownership of the earth and heavens. Acts 17:24 states that God is Lord of heaven and earth, while Deuteronomy 10:14 affirms that the heaven and the earth belong to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.5449999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 24, 44, 7, 48, 48, 'dwelleth not in temples made with hands', 'Divine Presence Beyond Temples', 'Both passages emphasize that God does not dwell in temples made with hands, highlighting a shared theme about the nature of God''s presence. This connection underscores the idea that the divine transcends physical structures.', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 24, 23, 66, 1, 1, 'dwelleth not in temples made with hands', 'Divine Presence Beyond Temples', 'Both passages emphasize God''s transcendence over physical structures. Acts 17:24 states that God does not dwell in temples, while Isaiah 66:1 questions the adequacy of a house built for Him.', 'theme', 0.524, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 24, 14, 6, 18, 18, 'dwelleth not in temples made with hands', 'God''s Presence Beyond Temples', 'Both passages emphasize God''s transcendence over physical structures. Acts 17:24 states that God does not dwell in temples made with hands, while 2 Chronicles 6:18 questions how God could dwell in a house built by man, highlighting His infinite nature.', 'theme', 0.51, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 24, 40, 11, 25, 25, 'Lord of heaven and earth', 'Connection of Lordship and Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize God as ''Lord of heaven and earth.'' This connection highlights the divine authority of God and His role in revealing truth to the humble.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 24, 19, 115, 16, 16, 'Lord of heaven and earth', 'Divine Sovereignty Over Creation', 'This connection highlights God''s sovereignty over both heaven and earth. Acts 17:24 emphasizes that God is the Lord of heaven and earth, while Psalms 115:16 notes that the earth is given to humanity, indicating a divine order in creation.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 25, 19, 50, 8, 13, 'he giveth to all life, and breath, and all things', 'Divine Sufficiency and Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize God''s self-sufficiency and ownership of all creation. Acts 17:25 states that God ''giveth to all life, and breath, and all things,'' while Psalms 50:12 declares, ''the world is mine, and the fulness thereof.'' This connection highlights the idea that God does not require human offerings.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 25, 1, 2, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Life and Breath', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''breath'' as essential for life. Acts 17:25 states that God gives life and breath, while Genesis 2:7 describes God breathing into man to give him life.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 25, 23, 42, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Breath', 'Both passages emphasize God''s role in giving breath and life to creation. Acts 17:25 states that God gives life and breath, while Isaiah 42:5 specifically mentions God giving breath to the people.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 25, 18, 33, 4, 4, 'breath, and all things', 'Connection of Life and Breath', 'Both passages emphasize the role of God in giving life. Acts 17:25 states that God gives ''life, and breath, and all things,'' while Job 33:4 highlights that ''the breath of the Almighty hath given me life.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 25, 44, 17, 28, 28, 'he giveth to all life', 'Connection of Life and Being', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of life and existence as derived from God. The idea that ''he giveth to all life'' in the source verse connects to ''in him we live'' in the target passage.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 25, 45, 11, 35, 35, 'he giveth to all life, and breath, and all things', 'Divine Self-Sufficiency Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s self-sufficiency. Both passages emphasize that God does not need anything from humanity, as He gives life and all things.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 25, 18, 22, 2, 2, 'he needed any thing', 'God''s Self-Sufficiency and Human Profitability', 'This connection highlights the idea that God does not need anything from humans, as He gives life and all things. Both passages emphasize the futility of thinking that human actions can profit God, suggesting His self-sufficiency.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 26, 5, 32, 7, 8, 'the bounds of their habitation', 'Divine Division of Nations', 'Both passages emphasize God''s role in determining the boundaries and inheritance of nations. Acts 17:26 speaks of all nations made from one blood, while Deuteronomy 32:8 describes the separation of nations and setting their bounds.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 26, 1, 3, 20, 20, 'one blood all nations of men', 'Unity of Humanity in Creation', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of a common origin for all people. Acts 17:26 refers to ''one blood'' for all nations, while Genesis 3:20 identifies Eve as ''the mother of all living.''', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 26, 39, 2, 10, 10, NULL, 'Unity of Humanity in Creation', 'Both passages emphasize the shared origin of humanity, highlighting that all nations are created from ''one blood'' and have ''one father.'' This connection underscores the importance of unity and mutual respect among people.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 26, 45, 5, 12, 19, 'one blood', 'Unity of Humanity and Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''one man'' as pivotal in the human experience. Acts 17:26 speaks to the unity of all nations from one blood, while Romans 5:12-19 discusses how sin entered through one man, Adam, affecting all humanity.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 26, 46, 15, 22, 22, 'one blood', 'Unity of Humanity in Christ', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''one blood'' in Acts 17:26, which emphasizes the shared humanity of all people. Similarly, 1 Corinthians 15:22 speaks to the universal impact of Adam''s sin and Christ''s redemption on all humanity.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 26, 46, 15, 47, 47, 'one blood', 'Connection of Humanity and Origins', 'This connection highlights the shared humanity in ''one blood'' and the distinction between the earthly and heavenly origins of humanity. Acts 17:26 emphasizes the unity of all nations, while 1 Corinthians 15:47 contrasts the first man with the second man from heaven.', 'theme', 0.377, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 26, 18, 14, 5, 5, NULL, 'Divine Determination of Boundaries', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine determination in both passages. Acts 17:26 speaks of God determining the bounds of nations, while Job 14:5 emphasizes that God has appointed bounds for individuals.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 27, 24, 23, 23, 24, 'though he be not far from every one of us', 'God''s Proximity to Humanity', 'Both passages emphasize that God is near to humanity and not distant. Acts 17:27 suggests seeking the Lord, while Jeremiah 23:23-24 asserts that God is a God at hand, filling heaven and earth.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
